One America, two peoples
New York — As I write this, officials across the United States are still counting votes for the 2020 US presidential election.
When the final tally is determined, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
In this closely contested election with record-high voter turnout, this was to be expected.
Only US citizens can vote for the US president, but this choice affects people all over.
If it is too early to determine the election results now, it is not too early to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful nation.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a powerful democratic nation.
Despite the actual restrictions related to the pandemic, voter participation remained high.
This process seems to be unfolding as planned.
Moreover, violent incidents are rare.
Courts are investigating decisions by the US Postal Service that seem politically motivated and hinder the delivery of ballots from areas where votes are expected to be mainly from Democrats.
U.S. President Donald Trump declared victory without any factual basis on Tuesday evening, and his demand to stop the count (at least in the states where he was leading) seemed to fall on deaf ears.
However, it is concerning that there is still a significant divide among American voters.
The candidates' votes were nearly equal.
It is not surprising that this division could lead to a divided government.
If this trend continues, the Democrats will win the White House and maintain control of the House of Representatives, while the Republicans will continue to control the Senate.
The governorships and seats in the state legislature were almost evenly split (with a slight advantage for the Republicans).
The expected "blue wave" for the Democrats did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a wide margin, securing around 4-5 million more votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
But Republicans held onto many seats in the Senate that many had predicted would flip, while Democrats lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result does not stem from strong authorization or political realignment.
Trump's polling numbers were excellent, with over 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter in US presidential candidate history and surpassing any previous winner.
Especially noteworthy is that this occurred against the backdrop of daily record-breaking new coronavirus cases and over 1,000 deaths.
As the consequences of his government's mishandling of the pandemic became most severe, nearly half of voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still wield significant influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems likely).
Even if he does not run himself, Trump is likely to exert a considerable influence on the choice of the Republican nominee in the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the parties of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
Unsurprisingly, despite lacking any evidence, Trump insisted on portraying himself as honorable and upright, attempting to invalidate the election results and accusing others of fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept Biden's presidency as legitimate.
Trump is likely never to concede defeat and will not attend the inauguration ceremony of the successor.
Quoting Will Rogers, Trump never encountered a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorized themselves into different communities and regions based on similar views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
And the absence of a national civics course facilitates the differentiation among generations.
It is worth noting that the differentiation within the country is not typically along economic lines.
People across different strata voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race did not overwhelmingly favor one over the other.
