Education level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geography. Republican voters tend to reside in exurbs and rural areas, while Democrats tend to live in urban areas.
However, culture may play a larger role in American politics than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy did not seem particularly important in the campaign, except in mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
In this context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the presidential election process or the functioning of government.
This situation is no different from reforming the United Nations Security Council.
Many believe that the current system has serious flaws lacking representation, but consensus on reforms is impossible because any potential solution would benefit some at the expense of others.
It is not surprising that those who stand to lose from the changes will resist them.
This will make governance difficult.
This depends largely on Senate Republican Leader Mitch McConnell and his ability and willingness to cooperate with the subsequent Biden presidency.
Collaboration will also require Biden to make compromises, which will certainly be resisted by more ideologically rigid members of his own party.
Democrats had tried to dismiss Trump and everything he stood for in a sharp manner.
They did not succeed.
And what Republicans sought was an election that would legitimize Trump.
And this did not achieve what they hoped.
Instead, the election revealed a nation and two categories of its citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can do so remains to be seen.
